Package com.iontrading.mkv

Class MkvRecord

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.iontrading.mkv.MkvObject
      • com.iontrading.mkv.MkvRecord
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    PrivateMkvRecord
    @Keep
@KeepPublicClassMemberNames
public class MkvRecord
extends MkvObject
    The MkvRecord class wraps a ION Bus Record in a Java Object.

    A Record is a dynamically structured collection of values; a MkvType object represents its structure.
    MkvRecord objects may be subscribed via subscribe methods, subsequent updates to a subscribed record are notified via MkvRecordListener listener invocations.

    Changes to the values of a MkvRecord may be done via supply methods (for local objects) or requested via transaction method (for both local and remote objects).

    Unless otherwise noted, passing a null argument to a constructor or method in this class will cause a NullPointerException to be thrown.

    See Also:
    MkvObject, MkvRecordListener, MkvSupply, MkvSupplyFactory, MkvPublishManager, MkvSubscribeManager, MkvTransactionListener, MkvTransactionCallEvent

        Publish this MkvObject.

        The ION Object represented by this MkvObject will be made available to the other components of the ION Platform this application is connected to.       • getLastMUTStamp

        public final double getLastMUTStamp()
        Provided both the publisher and the routing infrastructure support new timestamps, this method returns the timestamp of the latest supply action expressed in milliseconds, between the current time and midnight, January 1, 1970 UTC; the fractional part of the delay provides microsecond granularity.
        Returns:
        the last timestamp of this MkvRecord supply
        See Also:
        getLastMUTStampExt()

      • getLastMUTStampExt

        public final double getLastMUTStampExt()
        Suggested in place of getLastTStamp() and getLastMUTStamp()

        This method is provided as a helper for retrieving timestamps to be provided to the MkvE2EDelaySampler.sampleDelay(double) method.
        This is the recommended method to use if you need to compare timestamps because, in that use-case, it ensures backward compatibility with legacy publishers and routing infrastructure.

        Returns:
        • If the MkvRecord supports the new timestamp, this method returns the same value as getLastMUTStamp(), that is, the milliseconds elapsed between the current time and midnight, January 1, 1970 UTC.
          New timestamp is supported if publisher component uses a version of Java API greater equal to 136, or a version of C API greater equal to 146.
          Moreover, all the routers and platform bridges that are in the routing path between publisher and subscriber must be:
          • Router_m version 106 or higher
          • Platform Bridge version 103 or higher
        • Otherwise:
          • The timestamps cannot be referred to a specific time base (for example milliseconds from Epoch), but they can only be compared with each other.
          • The format of the result will also be expressed in milliseconds, but precision of the timestamp will depend from the value of the USEMSECS setting:
            • If USEMSECS = 0, the timestamp will have centi-seconds precision.
            • If USEMSECS = 1, the timestamp will have milliseconds precision. (default)
            • If USEMSECS = 2, the timestamp will have 10th of milliseconds precision.
            • If USEMSECS = 3, the timestamp will have microseconds precision.
        See Also:
        getLastMUTStamp()

      • supply

        public void supply​(String[] fields,
                   Object[] values)
            throws MkvObjectNotAvailableException,
                   MkvTypeNotFoundException,
                   MkvInvalidSupplyException
        Changes the values associated to this records and supply them to all local and remote subscribers.

        The arrays of fields and values must have the same size; each field will be updated with the corresponding value from these arrays.

        The runtime type of the values array may be also an array of any of the accepted Classes.
        Accepted classes are:

        • CharSequence (such as String, StringBuffer, StringBuilder) and MkvValue of type STR for STR fields
        • Double and and MkvValue of type REAL for REAL fields
        • Integer and MkvValue of type INT for INT fields
        • Integer, Date, Calendar, and MkvValue of type INT for DATE or TIME fields
        Parameters:
        fields - the array of field names.
        values - the array of values.
        Throws:
        MkvObjectNotAvailableException - if this MkvRecord is not available on the Platform.
        MkvTypeNotFoundException - if the type of this record is not available.
        MkvFieldNotFoundException - if a specified field is not part of this MkvRecord.
        MkvObjectNotLocalException - if this MkvRecord has not been created by this application.
        MkvInvalidSupplyException - if supply types don't match record types.

      • transaction

        public void transaction​(MkvSupply sup,
                        MkvTransactionCallListener lner)
                 throws MkvObjectNotAvailableException,
                        MkvTypeNotFoundException,
                        MkvInvalidSupplyException,
                        MkvConnectionException
        Requests a transaction on the specified record.

        Since the transaction request is an asynchronous operation, a transaction to either a local or remote record may produce no effect.
        Possibly a response is notified via a MkvTransactionCallListener listener invocation.

        Parameters:
        sup - a supply containing the changes to request.
        lner - a MkvTransactionCallListener to call on response.
        Throws:
        MkvObjectNotAvailableException - if this MkvRecord is not available.
        MkvTypeNotFoundException - if the type of this record is not available.
        MkvConnectionException - if the connection with the publisher of this MkvRecord has been broken.
        MkvInvalidSupplyException - if supply types don't match record types.

      • transaction

        public void transaction​(MkvSupply sup,
                        MkvCallerInfo info,
                        MkvTransactionCallListener lner)
                 throws MkvObjectNotAvailableException,
                        MkvTypeNotFoundException,
                        MkvInvalidSupplyException,
                        MkvConnectionException
        Requests a transaction on the specified record.

        Since the transaction request is an asynchronous operation, a transaction to either a local or remote record may produce no effect.
        Possibly a response is notified via a MkvTransactionCallListener listener invocation. This method is meant to be used by components which need to forward the information about the original caller to any downstream components. A component can retrieve the information about the original caller using MkvFunctionCallEvent.getCallerInfo(). Example: Suppose component A invokes a transaction on component B. In order to complete the business action, component B needs to invoke other transaction on downstream component C. In such scenario, component B can forward the information about the original caller A, so that component C knows the requests are actually coming on-behalf-of A.

        Parameters:
        sup - a supply containing the changes to request.
        info - the information about the original caller.
        lner - a MkvTransactionCallListener to call on response.
        Throws:
        MkvObjectNotAvailableException - if this MkvRecord is not available.
        MkvTypeNotFoundException - if the type of this record is not available.
        MkvConnectionException - if the connection with the publisher of this MkvRecord has been broken.
        MkvInvalidSupplyException - if supply types don't match record types.
        See Also:
        MkvCallerInfo, MkvTransactionCallEvent.getCallerInfo(), MkvTransactionCallListener

      • transactionWithId

        public int transactionWithId​(MkvSupply sup,
                             MkvTransactionCallListener lner)
                      throws MkvObjectNotAvailableException,
                             MkvTypeNotFoundException,
                             MkvInvalidSupplyException,
                             MkvConnectionException
        Requests a transaction on the specified record and returns the transaction id.

        This works the same as the transaction method, except that it returns the id for the transaction.
        It must be considered that for a transaction on a local record this method will return after both the transaction and the associated listener invocation.

        Parameters:
        sup - a supply containing the changes to request.
